Slot Types and Definitions (domain-specific and per-gold requirements):
- Rating: Any phrase referring to the dining quality, star level, or qualitative judgement of the restaurant. This includes explicit star ratings ("five star"), superlatives ("best"), or similar phrases ("highly rated").
- Amenity: Any mention of features, extra services, or accommodations provided by the establishment, e.g., "outdoor seating", "wifi", "buffet", "kid friendly", "delivery", "tie optional", or "outdoor dining area".
- Location: Any phrase, from single place names to whole prepositional phrases, indicating an area, street, landmark, or proximity-related location (e.g., "near here", "on 5th street", "downtown", "bridge st", "not too far", etc.). When the answer key omits prepositions, extract only the name ("bridge st" not "on bridge st"), otherwise, match the answer key for prepositional inclusion. Extract the smallest informative phrase matching the gold.
- Restaurant_Name: Exact names or short, commonly-used forms of specific restaurants as written in the query (e.g., "wendys", "markees", "ardens"). Only extract proper names, not generic descriptors.
- Price: Any explicit or qualified mention of price level or value, such as "cheap", "expensive", "under 20 dollars", "pricing good". Do not include generic or underspecified price mentions ("prices") unless qualified.
- Hours: Any expression referring to times of service, meal periods, or opening status, such as "open now", "late night", "for breakfast", "open at 11 pm", "stays open late like after 10 pm". When the gold slots expect detailed or descriptive time phrases, extract the entire phrase.
- Dish: Any specific named dish, food item, or menu item (e.g., "chicken tikka masala", "pizza"), but not generic categories ("main courses" is invalid unless a dish name is present).
- Cuisine: Phrases identifying a type or style of cooking, such as "italian", "bbq", "sushi", or composed/modified cuisines ("new mongolian bbq"). Always match the gold for scope; extract the full phrase ("new mongolian bbq" not just "mongolian bbq").

Extraction Rules:
- ONLY include slot types found in the query; DO NOT output keys for slots not present in the current query.
- For any slot, extract exactly the substring (span) from the query as it appears, matching spelling and casing. Do not paraphrase or standardize.
- For multi-word or descriptive slot values, if the gold expects a single phrase (e.g., "stays open late like after 10 pm"), extract the full phrase as-is, not split parts.
- DO NOT over-extract: avoid including surrounding words or prepositions beyond what is expected by the gold/answer key, and do not generalize (e.g., extract only "pizza" as "Dish" if that is the gold, do not call it "Cuisine" unless the gold does so). If in any doubt, follow the gold/answer key for phrase length and content.
- DO NOT extract generic, underspecified, or ambiguous terms that do not clearly meet the criteria and are not part of the gold standard (e.g., "main courses" not valid for "Dish", unqualified "prices" is not valid for "Price").
- DO NOT produce explanations, comments, or any output other than the specified JSON object mapping slots to [list of spans].
- Output a valid JSON object only, listing slot types (as above) as keys and arrays of extracted strings as values.

Input Format:
- You receive a query (natural language string).
- Output your result as a JSON object, with only the extracted slot values from the query string, following the detailed rules above.
